New Order in the Middle East
President Bush, Palestinian Prime Minister Mazen, and Israeli Prime Minister Sharon want to meet.
Is America serious about a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians?
How does this meeting fit into America's Middle East strategy?
Richard Haass, head of the planning staff at the US State Department, explains his "roadmap" for the entire Middle East.
What was achieved in Iraq - and what, with the help of Americans, the Iraqi people can now build - will determine the future of one of the most important countries in the Middle East.
An open, market-oriented, and peaceful Iraq could provide for reforms and growth throughout the entire region.
However, it will take some time until far-reaching changes in Iraq and throughout the entire Middle East take hold.
The challenge in Iraq after Saddam has humanitarian, security-policy, as well as economic and political aspects.
Thanks to the advanced planning of the Americans and the whole world, as well as the quick, focused, and goal-directed intervention of the coalition troops during the war, the humanitarian challenge is less severe than expected.
Hie und da gibt es Bedarf an humanitärer Hilfe, aber die angekündigte massive Krise ist glücklicherweise nie eingetreten.
Es gibt relativ wenige Flüchtlinge und Heimatvertriebene innerhalb des Irak. Die Versorgung mit Nahrungsmitteln, Wasser und Medikamenten ist in den meisten Fällen ausreichend oder bessert sich zumindest.
Die amerikanische Regierung hat über die UNO und Nichtregierungsorganisationen ungefähr 600 Millionen Dollar für unmittelbare humanitäre Hilfe zur Verfügung gestellt.
Überdies müssen wir im Irak die Grundordnung wiederherstellen.
Sicherheit ist die unabdingbare Voraussetzung für eine nachhaltige Verbesserung der Situation nach dem Krieg. Ohne Sicherheit können die Menschen ihr Land nicht wiederaufbauen, nicht zur Arbeit oder in Schulen zurückkehren.
Nach dem Sturz Saddams kam es zu einer Welle von Plünderungen, Gesetzlosigkeit und Abrechnungen.
Nun ist es oberste Priorität, dieser Gewalt ein Ende zu setzen.
Darüber hinaus muss es die Aufgabe internationaler Truppen sein, alle Massenvernichtungswaffen sicherzustellen und zu eliminieren, den gewaltvollen Ausbruch ethnischer und religiöser Konflikte zu verhindern und sicherzustellen, dass keiner der Nachbarn des Irak die ohnehin schon labile Situation noch verschlimmert.
Langfristig müssen wir den Irakern helfen, ihre Polizei- und Militärstrukturen wiederaufzubauen, so dass sie für ihre eigene Sicherheit sorgen können, ohne dabei jemanden zu bedrohen.
Der wirtschaftliche Wiederaufbau sollte genauer als wirtschaftliche Erneuerung betrachtet werden.
The physical capital is in better condition than expected and modern Iraq possesses a large reservoir of human capital.
In contrast to many other post-war scenarios, Iraq has plenty of raw materials to process.
The US is providing more than two billion dollars to support the initial reconstruction efforts.
Oil production will be raised to a better level.
To longer-term challenges belong an increase in oil production and the reduction of Iraq's enormous debt.
The decision of the UN Security Council to lift all sanctions is very welcome.
Given the many religious, ethnic, geographic, and political divides in Iraqi society, the assistance for political renewal in Iraq is likely the most challenging task.
The cynics and skeptics are wrong here.
The American goal – an intact Iraq where the law is respected and a democratic government emerges – is no pipe dream, especially not because Iraq has a literate population and a fairly large middle class.
The international community can achieve this goal if it is willing to continue following the course and cooperate with the Iraqis until the principles of a democratic society are realized.
Responsible Iraqi leaders must be supported so that the enormous political potential for constructive decisions can be utilized.
The developments in Iraq will undoubtedly have repercussions on the entire region, but they will not determine the fate of the Middle East.
Nearly no foreign policy issue engages and polarizes public opinion more strongly than the Palestinian question.
A little over a year ago, President George W. Bush declared his goal of a democratic Palestinian state living in peaceful coexistence with Israel.
In cooperation with Russia, the EU, and the United Nations, the US developed a roadmap that brings us incrementally closer to this goal.
A new Palestinian government and the new prime minister represent an important step in this direction.
Now, we must bring Palestinians and Israelis to set this process in motion and take measures to improve the situation, so that they can then tackle broader issues at the negotiating table.
Finally, it cannot be allowed that terrorists spoil the peace process for all time.
But a solution to the Palestinian issue is not automatically also the solution to all problems of the Middle East.
Clearly and unequivocally, the challenges that Iran poses to us are evident. This country is developing weapons of mass destruction and supported terrorism.
The latter mocks the norms and rules of the international community and isolates Iran and its people.
If Iran continues on this path, it will have consequences.
However, if Iran turns away from terrorism and the construction of catastrophic weapons, the USA is ready to take up good relations with this country again.
Just as the USA is willing to engage with Syria if substantial policy changes are achieved there.
A more general question is the relative lack of openness in the political and economic systems in the region.
For too long, America tolerated the "democratic exception" in the Muslim Middle East.
As long as the governments were friendly and supported regional stability, there was no reason for outsiders to advocate for a representative form of government.
We have painfully felt that closed political systems lead to resentments and extremism against the interests of the US, the West, and the entire world.
That's why we support democracy and political reforms through the Partnership Initiative for the Middle East, launched by Secretary of State Colin Powell in December 2002.
Even closed economic systems pose a danger.
Wie aus dem vorjährigen ,,Arab Human Development Report" (Bericht über den Entwicklungsstand der arabischen Länder) hervorgeht, blieben die arabischen Länder des Nahen Ostens in den Bereichen persönliche Freiheit, Frauenrechte, sowie wirtschaftliche und soziale Entwicklung weit hinter anderen Regionen zurück.
Zu lange haben diese Länder zusehen müssen, wie der wirtschaftliche Aufschwung an ihnen vorbei ging.
Präsident Bush ist entschlossen, die Vorteile wirtschaftlicher Freiheit mit den Arabern zu teilen.
Würde man seinen kürzlich geäußerten Vorschlag einer Freihandelszone zwischen den USA und dem Nahen Osten innerhalb eines Jahrzehnts realisieren, wäre das eine tragfähige Basis für eine solche Entwicklung.
